        "Create a six-column photosynthetic pathway comparison table: rows = C3, C4, CAM. Columns: (1) first stable product; (2) primary carboxylating enzyme; (3) cell types involved; (4) when stomata are open; (5) photorespiration rate at high temperature; (6) example crop or wild plant. Use this table for any question that begins 'Compare C3, C4, and CAM...'",
        "Create a four-column tropism comparison table: rows = phototropism, gravitropism, thigmotropism, chemotropism. Columns: (1) stimulus; (2) responding organ; (3) direction of response (positive/negative); (4) mechanism (hormone and cellular event). Add a fifth row for nastic responses and use it to show how nastics differ from tropisms in the 'direction of response' column.",
        "Create a comparison table of xerophyte adaptations and their Fick's law mechanism: rows = each adaptation (thick cuticle, sunken stomata, trichomes, rolled leaf, reduced leaf area, CAM). Columns: (1) adaptation; (2) which term in Fick's law it modifies (surface area, concentration gradient, or diffusion distance); (3) how it modifies that term; (4) other effects or trade-offs. This forces mechanistic rather than descriptive thinking about each feature.",
        "Create a comparison table of guard cell states: rows = open (daytime, well-watered), closed (night), closed (drought, ABA). Columns: (1) trigger; (2) K+ movement direction; (3) water movement direction; (4) guard cell turgor; (5) stomatal aperture; (6) net effect on CO2 and H2O exchange. This table consolidates all guard cell scenarios into one reference."
